## STEP 6 — Cross-Platform Integration Design

### Authentication

```
platform/sdk/auth/authClient.js   (shared logic)
        │
        ├── Web client        → localStorage token + AuthContext
        ├── Desktop (Electron) → Keychain (Keytar) + IPC bridge
        └── Mobile (RN)       → expo-secure-store / Keychain
        
All three → same JWT + refresh token protocol
Refresh token rotation handled in platform/sdk/auth/tokenManager.js
```

### WebSocket Messaging

```
server/src/socket/           (existing, unchanged)
     │  publishes events per platform/constants/socketEvents.js
     ↓
platform/sdk/socket/socketClient.js
     │  single Socket.IO client factory
     ├── Web → SocketContext.jsx consumes it
     ├── Desktop → ElectronSocketBridge.js wraps it
     └── Mobile → MobileSocketBridge.ts wraps it (background reconnect)

Event names: canonical registry in platform/constants/socketEvents.js
No platform ever hardcodes 'new_message' — always eventmap.NEW_MESSAGE
```

### Encryption Layer (E2EE)

```
platform/sdk/crypto/e2ee.js    (portable implementation)
     │  identical key derivation & encryption algorithm
     ├── Web    → uses SubtleCrypto (browser)
     ├── Desktop → Node.js crypto / SubtleCrypto in renderer
     └── Mobile → react-native-quick-crypto

Key Storage:
     ├── Web    → IndexedDB (encrypted at rest)
     ├── Desktop → OS Keychain via keytar
     └── Mobile → Keychain (iOS) / Keystore (Android)
     
platform/sdk/crypto/keyStorage.js abstracts all three
```

### Notifications

```
platform/sdk/notifications/notificationBridge.js
     │
     ├── Web    → ServiceWorker Web Push (existing)
     ├── Desktop → Electron Notification API + system tray badge
     └── Mobile → FCM (Android) + APNs (iOS) via @notifee

server/src/features/notifications/  (existing, unchanged)
     → sends push payload
     → platform bridge decides delivery mechanism
```

### File Uploads

```
platform/sdk/upload/uploadClient.js
     │  GCS presigned URL — same flow on all platforms
     ├── Web    → browser fetch (existing gcsProxy.js pattern)
     ├── Desktop → uses Node.js fs + electron IPC to pick files
     └── Mobile → react-native-document-picker + background upload

platform/sdk/upload/fileValidator.js  ← shared MIME / size rules
```

### AI Services

```
ai/api/ai.gateway.js  →  mounted as /api/v2/ai/* in server
     │
     ├── ai/orchestrator/   ← receives requests
     ├── ai/agents/         ← specialized processing
     ├── ai/memory/         ← vector retrieval
     └── ai/prompt-engine/  ← template injection

Client consumption:
     ├── Web    → existing aiService.js (update base URL to v2)
     ├── Desktop → same, via renderer bridge
     └── Mobile → MobileAIService.ts via platform/sdk/api

ai/services/LLMProvider.js supports:
     • google/gemini-2.0-flash  (default)
     • openai/gpt-4o            (fallback)
     • anthropic/claude-3-5     (premium tier)
```

---

## STEP 7 — Multi-Device Sync, Offline, Scalability

### Multi-Device Sync

```
server/src/socket/handlers/presence.socket.js  (existing)
     → tracks per-device presence

platform/sdk/sync/syncEngine.js  (new)
     → on reconnect: fetch delta since last_seen timestamp
     → apply locally, reconcile with offline queue
     → platform/sdk/sync/conflictResolver.js handles conflicts
```

### Offline Mode

```
platform/sdk/sync/offlineQueue.js
     ├── Web    → IndexedDB (idb-keyval)
     ├── Desktop → SQLite via better-sqlite3
     └── Mobile → WatermelonDB / MMKV

Queued actions: send_message, create_task, update_note
On reconnect → replay queue → server returns canonical IDs
```

### Scalable Backend Path (Current → Microservices)

```
Phase 1 (now):    Monolith server/ with feature modules
Phase 2 (6 mo):   Extract ai/ as standalone AI Service
                  ai/api/ai.gateway.js → separate port/process
Phase 3 (12 mo):  Extract notifications as service
Phase 4 (18 mo):  Full microservices with service mesh
                  Each server/src/features/* = deployable unit

API Gateway:      Nginx or AWS API Gateway for routing
Service comms:    REST internally or gRPC for performance-critical paths
Message bus:      Redis Pub/Sub → future: Kafka for high volume
```

---

## STEP 8 — Best Practices

### Code Reuse Strategy

| Layer | Reuse Mechanism |
|-------|----------------|
| Business logic | `platform/sdk/` — pure JS, no platform APIs |
| UI primitives | Web: `client/src/shared/components/ui/`, Mobile: mobile `/ui/` adapts same design language |
| Types | `platform/types/*.ts` — TypeScript interfaces shared |
| Constants | `platform/constants/` — event names, endpoints |

> **Rule**: If logic doesn't touch DOM or native APIs, it goes in `/platform/sdk`. Never duplicate it.

### Shared SDK Strategy

```
/platform/package.json  name: "@chttrix/sdk"
     → can be consumed via npm workspace (monorepo)
     → future: publish to private npm registry

Usage:
import { authClient } from '@chttrix/sdk/auth';
import { SOCKET_EVENTS } from '@chttrix/sdk/constants';
import { uploadFile } from '@chttrix/sdk/upload';
```

### API Versioning

```
Current:   /api/* (v1 implicit)
New:       /api/v2/ai/*  for AI Layer

server/routes/v1-to-v2-proxy.js (already exists!)
     → extend this to route /api/v2 to feature handlers
     
Rule: Never break v1 endpoints. Add capabilities in v2.
Deprecation: v1 sunset 12 months after v2 stable
platform/constants/apiVersions.js controls base URLs
```

### Platform Abstraction

```
Bridge Pattern:
  platform/sdk/[feature].js   ← abstract interface
       ↑           ↑           ↑
  Web bridge   Desktop bridge  Mobile bridge
(no bridge    (Electron IPC)  (RN native modules)
 needed, SDK   
 used directly)

Example: keyStorage.js
  interface: { save(key, value), load(key), delete(key) }
  Web impl:   IndexedDB
  Desktop:    Keytar (OS Keychain)
  Mobile:     expo-secure-store
```

